ek, Byzantine, and Syriac medicine to the Rabbinic-Talmudic medical discourses. This collection opens up new synchronic and diachronic perspectives in the study of the ancient traditions of recipe-books and medical collections. Besides the highly influential Galenic tradition, the contributions will focus on less studied Byzantine and Syriac sources as well as on the Talmudic tradition, which has never been systematically investigated in relation to medicine. This inquiry will highlight the overwhelming mass of information about drugs and remedies, which accumulated over the centuries and was disseminated in a variety of texts belonging to distinct cultural milieus. Through a close analysis of some relevant case studies, this volume will trace some paths of this transmission and transformation of pharmacological knowledge across cultural and linguistic boundaries, by pointing to the variety of disciplines and areas of expertise involved in the process.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Aug 2020) 0aMedicine in rabbinical literature. 0aMedicine, Ancient. 0aMedicine, Greek and Roman. 0aPharmacologyxByzantine Empire. 0aPharmacologyzByzantine Empire. 0aPharmacologyzByzantine empire. 4aGreek medical encyclopedias. 4aIntercultural history of knowledge and science. 4aLate Antique pharmacology/ pharmacotherapy. 4aTalmudic Medicine. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aLehmhaus, Lennart, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMartelli, Matteo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2017z978311071954308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z9783110625264